  "texts": [
    "Someone making this assumption might think that actions are just a particularly complex kind of ordinary physical event.",
    "Anscombe addresses this thought later on in Intention, where she notes that the actions of rational agents hold a special interest for us that other patterns in the causal order of the world do not:",
    "We notice changes and movements in the world without giving a comparable account of them [i.e.",
    "comparable to our account of actions].",
    "The tree waves in the wind; the movements of its leaves are as minute as the movement of my hand when I write on the blackboard, but we have no description of a pickedout set of movements or a picked out movement of the tree remotely resembling 'she wrote \"I am a fool\" on the blackboard' (p. 83)"
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}